# Research: Practical Tradeoffs for Effect-TS Test Frailty Mitigation

**Date:** 2026-05-15
**Context:** pi-soul-agent using Effect-TS v3.21+, @effect/vitest v0.29+, @effect/platform-node
**Agent:** researcher (2ef2ecbe)
**Tests analyzed:** `tests/services/loader.test.ts` (143 lines), `tests/services/soul-fs.test.ts` (97 lines)
**Source analyzed:** `src/loader.ts`, `src/services/soul-fs.ts`, `src/errors.ts`

---

## Issue A: Singleton Cache (`SoulSpecLoader.Default`) — Shared `Ref<Map>` Across Tests

**Problem:** `SoulSpecLoader` is an `Effect.Service` (implicit singleton). The `cache: Ref<Map>` is created once when the layer is first built and shared across all tests via `Effect.provide(SoulSpecLoader.Default)`. Test 3 (`listSouls returns []`) breaks if tests run in different order because earlier tests populate the cache.

### Options Comparison

| Approach                                                                         | Code Change                                                     | Risk                                                           | Confidence | Key Tradeoff                                                                             | Recommended?             |
| -------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| **1. `Layer.fresh`** — wrap `SoulSpecLoader.Default` in `Layer.fresh()` per test | ~3 chars per test (`Layer.fresh(...)`)                          | **Low** — no production changes, pure composition change       | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ | Most idiomatic Effect-TS; creates a new cache instance per test; zero production changes | **✅ YES — Recommended** |
| **2. `Layer.scoped`** — wrap layer in scope for per-test lifecycle               | Moderate — requires restructuring Service to be scoped          | **Medium** — changes production code interface                 | ⭐⭐⭐     | Overkill — service has no resource acquisition/release                                   | No                       |
| **3. Cache reset method** — expose `resetCache()` on service                     | Small: ~3 lines in Service + 1 line in `beforeEach`/`afterEach` | **Low** — but adds production API surface that shouldn't exist | ⭐⭐⭐     | Works with singleton but adds production API for testing                                 | No                       |
| **4. `Ref.set(cache, new Map())` in afterEach**                                  | ~4 lines in test file                                           | **Low** — no production changes                                | ⭐⭐⭐     | Hacky; race condition risk if tests ever parallelize                                     | Weak no                  |
| **5. `Layer.build` + `Effect.provide`** — build fresh layer per test             | Moderate                                                        | **Low**                                                        | ⭐⭐⭐⭐   | Complete isolation but more boilerplate than `Layer.fresh`                               | No                       |

### Winner: `Layer.fresh`

**Why:** `Layer.fresh` is the idiomatic Effect-TS mechanism for disabling layer memoization (see [Layer Memoization docs](https://effect.website/docs/requirements-management/layer-memoization/)). It creates a fresh, non-shared version of the layer every time it's provided. No production code changes. Minimal test code change.

```typescript
// BEFORE — shared singleton (Test 3 sees cache from Tests 1, 2)
it.effect("listSouls returns [] on empty cache", () =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const loader = yield* SoulSpecLoader;
    const souls = yield* loader.listSouls(1);
    expect(souls.length).toBe(0);
  }).pipe(
    Effect.provide(SoulSpecLoader.Default), // shared singleton
    Effect.provide(NodeFileSystemLayer),
    Effect.provide(NodePathLayer),
  ),
);

// AFTER — fresh layer per test (complete isolation)
it.effect("listSouls returns [] on empty cache", () =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const loader = yield* SoulSpecLoader;
    const souls = yield* loader.listSouls(1);
    expect(souls.length).toBe(0);
  }).pipe(
    Effect.provide(Layer.fresh(SoulSpecLoader.Default)), // fresh each time
    Effect.provide(NodeFileSystemLayer),
    Effect.provide(NodePathLayer),
  ),
);
```

**Key insight:** `Layer.fresh` wraps an existing layer and returns a new layer that is NOT memoized. Each `Effect.provide(Layer.fresh(...))` call creates a fresh cache instance. The `Ref<Map>` is re-created from scratch.

### Risk Analysis for Issue A

| Risk                                                                                                                                      | Mitigation                                                 |
| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- |
| If `Layer.fresh` is applied inconsistently, cache leakage persists                                                                        | Apply universally across all tests, or use a shared helper |
| `@effect/vitest` `it.layer` pattern shares layers globally. If future refactor adopts `it.layer`, `Layer.fresh` interaction needs testing | Stick with `Effect.provide` pattern for now                |
| Layer memoization bypass increases allocation cost                                                                                        | Negligible — `Ref<Map>` creation is cheap, tests are ~10   |

---

## Issue B: Real Filesystem Coupling — "bodhisattva-coder" Must Exist on Disk

**Problem:** Tests 1, 2, 4, 5, 8 (`loader.test.ts`) depend on `SoulSpecLoader.Default` backed by real `NodeFileSystemLayer`. They resolve "bodhisattva-coder" from `~/.pi/agent/souls/` or similar paths on the developer's machine. Fails on CI, other machines, or if the soul directory is missing.

### Options Comparison

| Approach                                                                                    | Code Change                                            | Risk                                           | Confidence | Key Tradeoff                                                                                           | Recommended?                   |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------- | ---------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------ |
| **1. `FileSystem.layerNoop`** (built-in mock FS)                                            | ~20-30 lines per mock setup                            | **Low** — uses existing `@effect/platform` API | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ | Official, maintained, typed mock FS with `Partial<FileSystem>` override pattern; no extra dependencies | **✅ YES — Primary**           |
| **2. Custom mock FileSystem layer**                                                         | ~80-120 lines implementing full `FileSystem` interface | **Medium** — needs to match the full interface | ⭐⭐⭐     | Total control but high maintenance; unnecessary when `FileSystem.layerNoop` exists                     | No                             |
| **3. Test fixture directory** (check in `tests/fixtures/souls/bodhisattva-coder/soul.json`) | ~5 fixture files, 1 env setup line                     | **Low** — works with real FS layer             | ⭐⭐⭐⭐   | Best for integration/e2e tests; CI must clone fixtures                                                 | **✅ YES — Combined approach** |
| **4. Inline fixtures via `Layer.succeed`**                                                  | ~10 lines per test                                     | **Low**                                        | ⭐⭐⭐     | Bypasses FS entirely; doesn't test FS-reading code paths                                               | Conditional                    |
| **5. Combined approach** — mock FS for unit tests, real fixtures for integration            | ~30 lines mock setup + fixture files                   | **Low**                                        | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ | Best coverage                                                                                          | **✅ YES — Recommended**       |

### Winner: `FileSystem.layerNoop` (Primary) + Fixture Directory (Integration)

**`FileSystem.layerNoop` from `@effect/platform` is the official testing mock.** It:

- Returns `Effect.fail` (not-found) for all FS operations by default
- Allows overriding specific methods with custom implementations
- Is type-safe via the `Partial<FileSystem>` parameter
- Has zero external dependencies beyond what's already installed (`@effect/platform` v0.96+)

```typescript
import { FileSystem } from "@effect/platform";
import { layer as NodePathLayer } from "@effect/platform-node/NodePath";

const SAMPLE_SOUL_MANIFEST = {
  name: "bodhisattva-coder",
  display_name: "Bodhisattva Coder",
  version: "1.0.0",
  spec_version: "0.5",
  description: "A coder bodhisattva",
  author: { name: "Test" },
  license: "MIT",
  tags: [],
  category: "general",
  compatibility: { models: [], frameworks: [] },
  allowed_tools: [],
  recommended_skills: [],
  files: { soul: "SOUL.md" },
  deprecated: false,
  environment: "virtual",
  interaction_mode: "text",
  sensors: [],
  actuators: [],
  soul_content: "hello",
  identity_content: "world",
};

const MockFileSystemLayer = FileSystem.layerNoop({
  exists: (path) => Effect.succeed(path.includes("bodhisattva-coder")),
  readFileString: (path) => {
    if (path.includes("soul.json")) {
      return Effect.succeed(JSON.stringify(SAMPLE_SOUL_MANIFEST));
    }
    if (path.includes("SOUL.md")) {
      return Effect.succeed("# Bodhisattva Coder Soul");
    }
    return Effect.fail(new FileSystemError({ message: "Not found", path, cause: null }));
  },
  readDirectory: (path) => Effect.succeed(["bodhisattva-coder"]),
});

// In test:
it.effect("getSoul auto-loads when soul not in cache", () =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const loader = yield* SoulSpecLoader;
    const soul = yield* loader.getSoul("bodhisattva-coder", 1);
    expect(soul.name).toBe("bodhisattva-coder");
  }).pipe(
    Effect.provide(Layer.fresh(SoulSpecLoader.Default)),
    Effect.provide(MockFileSystemLayer), // 🎯 mock FS instead of NodeFileSystemLayer
    Effect.provide(NodePathLayer),
  ),
);
```

### Risk Analysis for Issue B

| Risk                                                                                     | Mitigation                                                             |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `layerNoop` doesn't perfectly match real FS behavior (permissions, symlinks, edge cases) | Accept for unit tests; use real FS fixtures for integration tests      |
| Mock setup must be kept in sync with real manifest shape as SoulSpec evolves             | Use shared fixture constants; type-check against `SoulManifest`        |
| `resolveSoulPath` searches multiple directories — mock must handle all search paths      | Override `readDirectory` and `exists` comprehensively for search paths |

